When the finish-side sheet is **0.040 inch or thinner**, the **Double Dimple Method** is the fastest method of preparing the sheets. In this process, both sheets are dimpled before assembly. :contentReference[oaicite:3]{index=3}

💡 Memory Hook:
Thin skin → Double Dimple.

The key feature of the Pre-Dimple Method is that the sheets are separated, dimpled individually, and then reassembled. This method is used when the sheets are too thick or heavy to dimple together. :contentReference[oaicite:1]{index=1}

💡 Memory Hook:
**PRE = Prepare each sheet separately before assembly.**

Conventional pop rivets are commonly used for non-structural applications. They should not be installed where moderate or heavy structural loads are expected. :contentReference[oaicite:4]{index=4}

💡 Memory Hook:
Pop Rivet = Light Duty.

Aircraft are continuously subjected to vibration. In friction-lock rivets, the stem is retained mainly by friction and may loosen over time. Mechanical-lock rivets solve this problem by permanently locking the stem in place using a mechanical locking device. :contentReference[oaicite:0]{index=0}

💡 Memory Hook:
Vibration → Mechanical Lock.

CherryMAX is specifically designed to reduce installation costs because a single puller can install every rivet size. This is its greatest practical advantage over other mechanical-lock rivets. :contentReference[oaicite:2]{index=2}

🎯 Board Tip:
Economical + One Puller = CherryMAX.

Olympic-Lok is a lightweight mechanically-locking spindle-type blind rivet. During installation, its lock ring slides from the head down the stem to permanently lock the stem to the outer shell. :contentReference[oaicite:5]{index=5}

🎯 Board Tip:
If you see 'lightweight spindle-type,' immediately think Olympic-Lok.
